Measured instantaneously. To get better estimate of battery health,wait for about 10 seconds before starting the engine i.e. with Dashboard lights ON (keys in ACC-ON position).Battery health may be an issue if this voltage is below 11.5V
Coolant Temperature may go up 110°C. There may be several reasons for unusually high temperatures above this value - including leakage, blocked radiator, low coolant level, faulty sensor or others.

This system controls the Air - Fuel ratio that is injected in the engine - this ratio should be within a certain limit for the engine to operate properly.\nA problem within this system may affect fuel efficiency as more fuel may be injected to meet the exact ratio.

The fule injector (injector) system - monitors and controls the amount of fuel injected in the engine. Proper functioning of this system is required for peak engine performance, fuel economy and emission controls. Problems in this system could be caused because of damaged/choked injectors among several others.

This system monitors engine misfires.Misfiring is bad for catalytic converters (which is responsible for limiting pollution) as it means unburnt fuel which leads to dirty exhaust.\n There could be several triggers for misfires including misbehaving spark plugs, injectors or even faulty sensors among others

This system monitors the performance of Exhaust Gas Recirculation, Secondary Air Injection, Catalyst Health or the Evaporation System (which controls fuel vapours).\n All of these subsystems are directly responsible for vehicle emission (pollution) controls
These set of monitors are for checking malfunction in speed sensors, the value controlling idle speed of engine, engine oil pressure among several other parameters.
This system monitors errors in various computer subsystem in the vehicle or in communication between this subsystems.

The transmission system consists of the complete drivetrain including clutch, gearbox, rear axie etc.\n A problem in the transmission system affects the vehicle drivability. Problems could be due to speed sensor malfunction, problems with gear ratio, torque convertor etc.
All problems realated to vehicle Chassis, Body (ex - Airbags, Seatbelts) or Internal Communication between vehicles computer sub systems are reported in this section.
